00:41:01.580 --> 00:41:04.670
But if you read Nietzsche in
the original, what he really

00:41:04.670 --> 00:41:06.980
meant by the
ubermensch was someone

00:41:06.980 --> 00:41:11.120
who could master the
lowest parts of himself.

00:41:11.120 --> 00:41:16.610
Someone who could overcome
the worst aspects of himself.

00:41:16.610 --> 00:41:20.630
And in the freedom that he
gained from his own lower

00:41:20.630 --> 00:41:25.840
parts, he could become the
person he was meant to be.

00:41:25.840 --> 00:41:29.510
It was inner freedom,
inner mastery.

00:41:29.510 --> 00:41:34.870
Now, closely related
to the idea of freedom

00:41:34.870 --> 00:41:37.250
is the idea of confidence.

00:41:37.250 --> 00:41:39.400
Let me demonstrate
that this way.

00:41:39.400 --> 00:41:43.060
It's almost the
first of January.

00:41:43.060 --> 00:41:44.560
January first, New Year's.

00:41:44.560 --> 00:41:47.920
We all make resolutions
on January first.

00:41:47.920 --> 00:41:49.870
Let's say my New
Year's resolution

00:41:49.870 --> 00:41:54.160
is I'm really going to cut down
on sugars and carbs this year.

00:41:54.160 --> 00:41:56.659
This year, this is the year.

00:41:56.659 --> 00:41:57.700
I'm going to lose weight.

00:41:57.700 --> 00:42:00.280
I'm really going to
watch what I eat, OK?

00:42:00.280 --> 00:42:04.710
And let's say on January
fourth, I have a donut.

00:42:04.710 --> 00:42:07.060
And on January fifth,
I have five donuts.

00:42:07.060 --> 00:42:10.150
And by January seventh, I've
forgotten the whole resolution,

00:42:10.150 --> 00:42:13.120
which is usually what happens.

00:42:13.120 --> 00:42:16.630
How confident can I be?

00:42:16.630 --> 00:42:18.220
Think about it.

00:42:18.220 --> 00:42:23.230
A big part of confidence
is self-credibility.

00:42:23.230 --> 00:42:29.000
Do I believe the commitments
I make to myself?

00:42:29.000 --> 00:42:32.150
If the answer is yes,
if I make a commitment,

00:42:32.150 --> 00:42:34.340
I am going to carry it through.

00:42:34.340 --> 00:42:36.530
I will be confident.

00:42:36.530 --> 00:42:40.130
But most people,
sadly can't say that.

00:42:40.130 --> 00:42:43.680
If they're honest with
themselves, they'll admit,

00:42:43.680 --> 00:42:44.930
I make a commitment to myself.

00:42:44.930 --> 00:42:46.940
I'm good for a day,
maybe two days.

00:42:46.940 --> 00:42:49.130
By day three, I'm
already cheating.

00:42:49.130 --> 00:42:53.580
And by day five, I've forgotten
I even made the commitment.

00:42:53.580 --> 00:42:58.310
It is mathematically impossible
to have confidence in yourself

00:42:58.310 --> 00:43:01.640
if you can't even carry
out the commitments you

00:43:01.640 --> 00:43:02.810
make to yourself.

00:43:06.270 --> 00:43:09.510
And it's impulses that
erode your ability

00:43:09.510 --> 00:43:14.820
to carry out those commitments
because they stop you.

00:43:14.820 --> 00:43:16.630
I have a couple
of quotes on this

00:43:16.630 --> 00:43:20.370
that I think are
particularly pithy about it.

00:43:20.370 --> 00:43:23.980
Leonardo da Vinci
said, "You will never

00:43:23.980 --> 00:43:26.080
have a greater or
lesser dominion

00:43:26.080 --> 00:43:29.050
than that over yourself.

00:43:29.050 --> 00:43:34.510
The height of a person's success
is gauged by his self-mastery.

00:43:34.510 --> 00:43:39.580
The depth of his failure
by his self-abandonment."

00:43:39.580 --> 00:43:43.160
So it's mastery over self,
mastery over impulses.

00:43:43.160 --> 00:43:49.090
Lao Tzu, the founder of Taoism,
said it even more succinctly.

00:43:49.090 --> 00:43:52.270
"He who conquers
others is strong,

00:43:52.270 --> 00:43:56.420
but he who conquers
himself is mighty."

00:43:56.420 --> 00:43:57.540
That's the true strength.

00:44:00.210 --> 00:44:02.640
And finally, leadership.

00:44:02.640 --> 00:44:05.970
Again, I'm going to define
leadership as just the ability

00:44:05.970 --> 00:44:08.850
to have a positive impact
on those around you.

00:44:08.850 --> 00:44:12.000
Whether it's your family, your
coworkers, or the community

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:13.190
at large.

00:44:13.190 --> 00:44:15.030
And I'm going to give
you a micro-example

00:44:15.030 --> 00:44:16.230
and a macro-example.

00:44:16.230 --> 00:44:23.400
The micro-example brings
us back to Susan and Marty,

00:44:23.400 --> 00:44:26.202
the crazy couple that
I introduced you to

00:44:26.202 --> 00:44:26.910
at the beginning.

00:44:26.910 --> 00:44:30.660
These were parents who were
trying to get their daughter

00:44:30.660 --> 00:44:34.950
to control her
impulses when every day

00:44:34.950 --> 00:44:37.890
she saw them giving
in to their impulses.

00:44:37.890 --> 00:44:41.100
So obviously, they could
not be good leaders.

00:44:41.100 --> 00:44:44.820
So as a therapist, I said, we're
not working on your daughter.

00:44:44.820 --> 00:44:47.730
I'm sorry, but we're
working on you.

00:44:47.730 --> 00:44:50.010
You have to use the
black sun tool, Marty,

00:44:50.010 --> 00:44:51.750
to control your
temper and to control

00:44:51.750 --> 00:44:54.870
your gambling You, Susan,
have to use the black sun

00:44:54.870 --> 00:44:58.710
tool to control your
eating and your confiding

00:44:58.710 --> 00:44:59.722
in your daughter.

00:44:59.722 --> 00:45:01.930
And fortunately, with their
daughter's life at stake,

00:45:01.930 --> 00:45:03.710
they worked really
hard on themselves.

00:45:03.710 --> 00:45:06.720
So pretty quickly, they
actually gained some control

00:45:06.720 --> 00:45:07.950
over themselves.

00:45:07.950 --> 00:45:10.560
That also enabled them
to talk to one another

00:45:10.560 --> 00:45:13.210
without constantly
getting into an argument.

00:45:13.210 --> 00:45:15.820
And then, they could
agree on limits they

00:45:15.820 --> 00:45:17.490
could set with their daughter.

00:45:17.490 --> 00:45:20.550
And their daughter could
feel that they were actually

00:45:20.550 --> 00:45:22.680
credibly setting those
limits because they

00:45:22.680 --> 00:45:24.520
weren't reactive or impulsive.

00:45:24.520 --> 00:45:25.590
They were simply, look.

00:45:25.590 --> 00:45:26.880
This is the rule.

00:45:26.880 --> 00:45:28.840
If you steal money, you
spend too much money,

00:45:28.840 --> 00:45:30.300
your allowance disappears.

00:45:30.300 --> 00:45:32.400
You know, or whatever
the limits were.

00:45:32.400 --> 00:45:36.510
So they became leaders
within their family.

00:45:36.510 --> 00:45:38.310
And you don't have
to have a family

00:45:38.310 --> 00:45:39.600
to witness this happening.

00:45:39.600 --> 00:45:41.880
I recommend that you
use the black sun

00:45:41.880 --> 00:45:45.090
tool every single time
you have an impulse

00:45:45.090 --> 00:45:47.880
and watch the people around
you over the next two

00:45:47.880 --> 00:45:49.810
weeks or four weeks.

00:45:49.810 --> 00:45:53.550
You will see them paying
more respect to you.

00:45:53.550 --> 00:45:55.980
And you'll even see
them emulating you,

00:45:55.980 --> 00:45:58.650
even if they have no idea
that you're using this tool.

00:45:58.650 --> 00:46:02.760
They'll just get the vibe of a
person who has more authority.

00:46:02.760 --> 00:46:05.500
I've seen it over
and over again.

00:46:05.500 --> 00:46:08.770
Now, let me give
you a macro-example.

00:46:08.770 --> 00:46:14.680
This is an example of a
movement that because it

00:46:14.680 --> 00:46:18.990
had an extraordinary
degree of self-restraint

00:46:18.990 --> 00:46:23.100
was actually able to
have a tremendous impact

00:46:23.100 --> 00:46:24.080
on the whole society.

00:46:24.080 --> 00:46:25.800
I'm talking about the
early civil rights

00:46:25.800 --> 00:46:29.004
movement of the late
'50s and early '60s.

00:46:29.004 --> 00:46:30.420
I've studied this
because I've met

00:46:30.420 --> 00:46:32.753
with one of the leaders of
that movement, Reverend James

00:46:32.753 --> 00:46:36.990
Lawson, who brought Gandhi
and nonviolent techniques

00:46:36.990 --> 00:46:38.490
to the civil rights movement.

00:46:38.490 --> 00:46:39.990
He basically taught
those techniques

00:46:39.990 --> 00:46:42.570
to Martin Luther
King and John Lewis.

00:46:42.570 --> 00:46:44.940
And what's amazing
about that movement

00:46:44.940 --> 00:46:49.860
is that its success was because
it was incredibly disciplined.

00:46:49.860 --> 00:46:54.150
There were absolutely no
spontaneous demonstrations.

00:46:54.150 --> 00:46:58.470
Every single demonstration
was meticulously planned.

00:46:58.470 --> 00:47:00.990
Participants were vetted.

00:47:00.990 --> 00:47:04.740
And sometimes, rejected or
moved to other positions

00:47:04.740 --> 00:47:09.060
if they couldn't
control themselves.

00:47:09.060 --> 00:47:13.060
The goals of the movement
were kept very limited.

00:47:13.060 --> 00:47:15.980
Of course, they wanted to
desegregate the entire South,

00:47:15.980 --> 00:47:18.930
the schools, the neighborhoods,
the government, everything.

00:47:18.930 --> 00:47:22.650
Instead, they picked
one lunch counter

00:47:22.650 --> 00:47:26.580
in one department
store in one town

00:47:26.580 --> 00:47:30.030
and decided to have
a sit-in there.

00:47:30.030 --> 00:47:32.430
And they picked the department
store based on the fact

00:47:32.430 --> 00:47:34.835
that a lot of blacks shopped
at that department store,

00:47:34.835 --> 00:47:36.210
because they knew
they were going

00:47:36.210 --> 00:47:39.390
to end up having to boycott
that department store.

00:47:39.390 --> 00:47:43.560
So very limited, targeted
goals that then they were

00:47:43.560 --> 00:47:46.410
able to expand to other goals.

00:47:46.410 --> 00:47:49.080
And the most dramatic
example of self-restraint

00:47:49.080 --> 00:47:52.500
was that they trained
themselves to not

00:47:52.500 --> 00:47:57.720
respond to physical
and verbal assaults.

00:47:57.720 --> 00:48:01.320
Not only from white bystanders,
but from the police.

00:48:01.320 --> 00:48:06.390
They remained polite and
soft spoken at all times.

00:48:06.390 --> 00:48:09.480
You want an even more
dramatic example?

00:48:09.480 --> 00:48:14.850
Gandhi's movement in India,
an entire national movement

00:48:14.850 --> 00:48:16.230
of millions.

00:48:16.230 --> 00:48:18.510
Most of whom had
never met Gandhi

00:48:18.510 --> 00:48:22.110
remained, for the most part,
peaceful and nonviolent.

00:48:22.110 --> 00:48:26.010
And they brought down
the British empire.

00:48:26.010 --> 00:48:27.870
The bottom line
here is if you want

00:48:27.870 --> 00:48:32.550
to have an enduring impact
on the people around you

00:48:32.550 --> 00:48:37.140
your family, your coworkers,
or the society at large,

00:48:37.140 --> 00:48:39.900
you must practice
self-restraint.

00:48:39.900 --> 00:48:43.650
You must learn to
control your impulses.

00:48:43.650 --> 00:48:46.950
And when you do, you not
only improve your own life.

00:48:46.950 --> 00:48:52.020
You actually send out a rippling
wave of self-contained energy

00:48:52.020 --> 00:48:55.010
to those around you who
want to emulate that.

00:48:57.830 --> 00:48:59.880
Now, I want to
spend a little bit

00:48:59.880 --> 00:49:04.230
of time just about our
society and where we're at.

00:49:04.230 --> 00:49:09.030
Because let's be honest, impulse
control is at an all-time low.

00:49:09.030 --> 00:49:11.700
I shouldn't laugh, but
it is kind of ridiculous.

00:49:11.700 --> 00:49:14.100
I mean, in preparation
for this workshop,

00:49:14.100 --> 00:49:18.780
I tried to think of one
single major cultural

00:49:18.780 --> 00:49:21.840
or governmental
institution that hasn't

00:49:21.840 --> 00:49:26.280
been infected with the
disease of self-indulgence.

00:49:26.280 --> 00:49:29.970
And I couldn't think
of a single one.

00:49:29.970 --> 00:49:31.050
Organized religion.

00:49:31.050 --> 00:49:34.380
You've got Catholic
pedophilia scandals.

00:49:34.380 --> 00:49:35.230
Sports.

00:49:35.230 --> 00:49:38.460
You've got doping,
Penn State pedophilia,

00:49:38.460 --> 00:49:41.370
violence against women.

00:49:41.370 --> 00:49:42.900
Banking.

00:49:42.900 --> 00:49:45.610
I remember when I was growing
up in the '50s, bankers were

00:49:45.610 --> 00:49:46.110
like--

00:49:46.110 --> 00:49:48.390
I thought they were the
most conservative people

00:49:48.390 --> 00:49:49.180
in the world.

00:49:49.180 --> 00:49:50.940
I mean, if I'm going
to start a rock band,

00:49:50.940 --> 00:49:53.370
I'm calling it Wells Fargo
and the wolves of Wall Street.

00:49:53.370 --> 00:49:56.640
It's crazy.

00:49:56.640 --> 00:49:58.320
Government.

00:49:58.320 --> 00:49:59.750
It's just a cesspool.

00:49:59.750 --> 00:50:00.870
It's a cesspool.

00:50:00.870 --> 00:50:04.920
And whatever you think of Trump,
he cannot restrain himself from

00:50:04.920 --> 00:50:09.630
these early morning tweets, even
when they defeat his own cause.

00:50:09.630 --> 00:50:12.630
That's lack of impulse control.

00:50:12.630 --> 00:50:15.450
I'm not sure why anyone ever
looked up to the entertainment

00:50:15.450 --> 00:50:18.710
industry, but the entertainment
industry is, again,

00:50:18.710 --> 00:50:20.730
a kind of a cesspool.

00:50:20.730 --> 00:50:21.740
The press.

00:50:21.740 --> 00:50:27.720
There been sexual harassment
scandals at Fox, NBC, NPR.

00:50:27.720 --> 00:50:32.340
I didn't even know they had
sex at NPR, which is like,

00:50:32.340 --> 00:50:34.260
who would think of it?

00:50:34.260 --> 00:50:37.740
My point is that
every institution

00:50:37.740 --> 00:50:42.150
that we might want to
look up to as role models

00:50:42.150 --> 00:50:44.790
is already infected
with the disease.

00:50:44.790 --> 00:50:48.930
It looks like we're going to
have to be the antibodies.

00:50:48.930 --> 00:50:54.390
Clearly, the change isn't
going to come from top down.

00:50:54.390 --> 00:50:57.360
In a sense, the change
has to come from us

00:50:57.360 --> 00:51:00.810
or as Gandhi said it,
we must be the change

00:51:00.810 --> 00:51:03.600
we wish to see in the world.

00:51:03.600 --> 00:51:06.990
Now, the good news is,
if you believe Carl Jung,

00:51:06.990 --> 00:51:09.340
we are all connected
to one another.

00:51:09.340 --> 00:51:12.510
This is inherent in his notion
of a collective unconscious.

00:51:12.510 --> 00:51:15.540
That there's a realm
in which all of us

00:51:15.540 --> 00:51:20.190
sort of share the same
mythologies, the same imagery,

00:51:20.190 --> 00:51:23.460
the same sense that
we're all connected,

00:51:23.460 --> 00:51:28.230
which means that if we can
work really hard on ourselves,

00:51:28.230 --> 00:51:31.390
we may actually affect
the rest of the society.

00:51:31.390 --> 00:51:34.770
What Margaret Mead said about
this, by the way, is that--

00:51:34.770 --> 00:51:37.410
never doubt that a small
group of committed citizens

00:51:37.410 --> 00:51:40.080
can change an entire society.

00:51:40.080 --> 00:51:44.250
And she added, it's the
only thing that ever has.

00:51:44.250 --> 00:51:46.950
So just as an end
exercise here, I

00:51:46.950 --> 00:51:50.220
want to give you a taste
for what we, as a group,

00:51:50.220 --> 00:51:55.170
could create in terms of the
spirit of self-restraint.

00:51:55.170 --> 00:51:58.710
So close your
eyes, and I'm going

00:51:58.710 --> 00:52:01.590
to run you through the black
sun tool one last time.

00:52:01.590 --> 00:52:05.120
And then, I'm going to
add some stuff at the end.

00:52:05.120 --> 00:52:09.460
So once again, start with
the feeling of deprivation.

00:52:09.460 --> 00:52:12.550
Those little kid feelings of
not getting what you want.

00:52:12.550 --> 00:52:15.940
And feel them as
intensely as you can.

00:52:19.540 --> 00:52:21.250
Now, let go of the
thing that you want.

00:52:21.250 --> 00:52:26.040
And with it, let the entire
outside world disappear.

00:52:26.040 --> 00:52:29.220
And redirect your
attention inside yourself.

00:52:32.470 --> 00:52:35.380
Face the void.

00:52:35.380 --> 00:52:37.350
Be calm.

00:52:37.350 --> 00:52:38.640
Just be curious about it.

00:52:41.280 --> 00:52:45.360
And imagine the black sun begins
to ascend from the deepest

00:52:45.360 --> 00:52:46.837
part of the void.

00:52:50.740 --> 00:52:57.700
Expanding slowly, it fills you
with it's warm and limitless

00:52:57.700 --> 00:52:58.200
energy.

00:53:01.820 --> 00:53:04.940
Now, redirect your attention
back to the outside world.

00:53:04.940 --> 00:53:08.520
And let the black sun
energy surge out of you

00:53:08.520 --> 00:53:13.526
in a flow of infinite giving
to everyone around you.

00:53:18.234 --> 00:53:20.400
Now I'd like you to imagine
that everyone around you

00:53:20.400 --> 00:53:21.920
is also using the tool.

00:53:21.920 --> 00:53:25.320
So they're generating
light, encouraging

00:53:25.320 --> 00:53:26.580
you to shine brighter.

00:53:26.580 --> 00:53:29.660
And your light is encouraging
them to shine brighter.

00:53:35.550 --> 00:53:37.130
And what I'd like
you to imagine next

00:53:37.130 --> 00:53:40.140
is that the light coalesces.

00:53:40.140 --> 00:53:42.900
And essentially,
forms a sun rising

00:53:42.900 --> 00:53:46.650
above the center of the room
more powerful than anything

00:53:46.650 --> 00:53:49.380
that we could create,
each of us, on our own.

00:53:52.600 --> 00:53:56.090
And imagine that that sun
can reach beyond this room

00:53:56.090 --> 00:53:58.229
and shine on the entire society.

00:54:04.460 --> 00:54:07.800
In a few minutes, we'll disperse
and go our own separate ways.

00:54:07.800 --> 00:54:09.840
But imagine that the
power of this sun

00:54:09.840 --> 00:54:13.110
remains available
to all of us as we

00:54:13.110 --> 00:54:18.630
battle our own individual
impulses on our own.

00:54:18.630 --> 00:54:21.780
In a way, it reaffirms
an enduring truth,

00:54:21.780 --> 00:54:25.938
which is we are never
completely on our own.

00:54:37.360 --> 00:54:40.712
And when you're ready,
you can open your eyes.

00:54:40.712 --> 00:54:41.920
Thank you so much for coming.

00:54:41.920 --> 00:54:43.520
I really appreciate it.

00:54:43.520 --> 00:54:44.020
Thank you.

00:54:44.020 --> 00:54:47.070
[APPLAUSE]

